---
export const prerender = true;

import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import GoldCalculator from "../components/GoldCalculator";
import { getCanonicalUrl } from "../lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Gold Price Calculator | Grams Tola Sovereign to INR & USD"
  description="Convert gold prices across grams, tola, sovereign, and kilograms using the current benchmark gold rate for your city."
  canonical={getCanonicalUrl("/gold-price-calculator")}
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 py-12 md:px-6">
    <div class="mb-8 max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.24em] text-amber-700">Calculator</p>
      <h1 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-gray-950">Convert grams, tola, sovereign, and kilograms into today’s gold value.</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-8 text-gray-600">
        Choose your city and karat once, then adjust the weight freely without extra API calls. The calculator keeps the interaction fast by converting units locally after the benchmark price is fetched.
      </p>
    </div>

    <GoldCalculator client:load />

    <article class="mt-10 rounded-4xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-[0_24px_80px_-44px_rgba(17,24,39,0.3)] md:p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-950">Understanding common gold weight units in India</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-base leading-8 text-gray-600">
        <p>
          Gold is still quoted in several parallel unit systems depending on whether you are buying jewellery, comparing bullion products, or discussing family savings. Grams remain the clearest unit for retail comparison, especially when jewellers publish per-gram or per-10-gram rates.
        </p>
        <p>
          Tola is an older South Asian weight measure that continues to appear in bullion conversations and cross-border trade. One tola equals 11.664 grams, while one sovereign equals 8 grams and is still common in South Indian jewellery buying.
        </p>
        <p>
          Kilograms matter more for wholesale, professional bullion desks, and larger treasury-style calculations, but the conversion is still useful for high-value estimation. The goal is to separate the benchmark metal value from making charges, wastage, and dealer premiums.
        </p>
        <p>
          This calculator fetches the price only when city or karat changes. Every weight adjustment after that is local math, which keeps the interaction fast while preserving an honest benchmark.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>